    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following for the five candidate services: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice.\n1) Read metric.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(timestamp, unit='s', utc=True). 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 using the full available series (do NOT filter before computing P95). 3) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-15 21:21:06 UTC to 2024-01-15 21:51:06 UTC inclusive. 4) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) where cmdb_id is one of the five candidates, mark anomaly points where value > global_P95. 5) Identify consecutive anomalous runs (consecutive timestamps within the filtered window). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) produce a compact summary row with these fields: component, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, total_anomalous_points, number_of_anomalous_runs, longest_run_length (in minutes/points), earliest_run_start_utc, max_value_in_window, max_exceed_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95. 6) Return the compact table limited to these five services, sorted by total_anomalous_points descending then max_exceed_ratio descending. Also return the count of groups scanned (rows in this table) and how many had number_of_anomalous_runs > 0. Keep output to top 20 rows and do not print raw time series."}

{
    "analysis": "We ran the prescribed workflow: computed global P95 thresholds on full series, filtered to the incident window, ran metric-level anomaly detection for the five candidate services, and examined trace anomalies for those services. Findings: (1) metrics show brief, correlated spikes across workload/row_count, latency, CPU and memory in many services during 21:24–21:48 UTC; (2) trace telemetry shows elevated row_count flowing from frontend into downstream services, with early anomalies at productcatalogservice and recommendationservice (~21:25 UTC) and clear anomalies for checkoutservice traces and durations starting ~21:24 UTC; (3) checkoutservice exhibits the largest relative latency spike among the five candidates (latency-90 exceeded P95 by ~21%, earliest anomalous point 2024-01-15 21:24:00 UTC) and duration_p95/duration_mean anomalies at the same time. Logs contain increased log.row_count but no error_count increases; error_logs.csv is empty. The pattern is consistent with a short-lived traffic/request surge that propagated through frontend to downstream services and caused transient resource pressure and latency increases. According to the trace-localization rule (choose the most downstream faulty service in the call chain), checkoutservice is the most likely root-cause service among the candidate set because it is both downstream in traces and shows the largest/earliest service-level degradation.",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Diagnosis summary (final answer):\nRoot-cause service/component: checkoutservice\nFailure reason: transient workload/traffic surge causing resource pressure (manifested as increased latency and short-lived resource usage spikes) — best mapped to \"high memory usage\" / resource pressure at checkoutservice.\nEstimated start: first anomalous checkoutservice signal ~2024-01-15 21:24:00 UTC (latency/duration spikes). Evidence: checkoutservice shows the highest relative latency spike (latency-90 exceeded P95 by ~21%, earliest 21:24 UTC) and trace duration anomalies at the same time; traces show elevated request (row_count) flow into checkoutservice from frontend and other services; logs show increased row_count across services but no error_count spikes, supporting a traffic surge rather than socket/network errors. Recommendation: treat this as a transient traffic-induced resource pressure on checkoutservice (investigate autoscaling, request throttling, and memory/heap sizing for checkoutservice)."
}

Summary:
Root cause identified as checkoutservice experiencing transient resource pressure (memory-related) triggered by a short traffic surge starting ~2024-01-15 21:24:00 UTC. Evidence: trace row_count spikes into checkoutservice and concurrent checkoutservice latency/duration anomalies; metric memory and workload spikes across services; logs show increased row_count but no error_count spikes (points to traffic-induced resource pressure rather than socket/network errors).

